node.text:
I know your back to school “to-do” list is already a mile long… but what about your “to-don’t” list? ❌

Sometimes your “to-don’t” list is even more important than your “to-do” list.

These are my constant reminders to myself (especially at the start of a new school year):

1️⃣ Don’t compare yourself - This includes your classroom, teaching style, the way you spend your time, and more. Be confident in what makes you unique and remember that you are enough exactly as you are.

2️⃣ Don’t forget to prioritize - So often, the things that NEED to get done aren’t always the most fun but they are the items that move the needle forward. Focus on doing the hard stuff now so you can enjoy the easy stuff later. It’s worth it.

3️⃣ Don’t stretch yourself too thin - You can only add so much to your plate before you have to start taking items off. My go-to motto is: If it isn’t a heck yes, it’s a no. Keep this in mind every time you get asked to take on a new responsibility.

4️⃣ Don’t buy things you don’t need - I’m looking at you Target! If you aren’t 100% positive you need it, just wait to buy it. Chances are, after a few days, you will forget about it (and save yourself money in the meantime).

What’s on your “to-don’t” list currently and how do you remind yourself? 👇🏻 Let’s chat in the comments! 🖤

node.text:
“Answering emails is my favorite!”
- Said no one ever 😬

If answering emails is sucking up a lot of your time as a teacher, keep reading! 👇🏼

I’d be willing to bet that a lot of the emails you send are repetitive. You’re sending emails about academic progress, attendance, behavior, and more… Again. And again. And again. 📧

Stop. Reinventing. The. Wheel. ❌

One of the best time-savers I discovered as a teacher is USING EMAIL TEMPLATES!

I know what you’re probably thinking… “I don’t have time to make the templates though” 😫

I’VE GOT YOU COVERED! 😉 I’ve put together 5 of my most-often used email templates and I’m giving them to you FOR FREE! 🎉

You can use the link in my profile (and then click “FREEBIES”) or type this url in your address bar to grab the free templates:
www.pocketfulofprimary.com/freebies

Tag a friend and save them some time! ⏰🖤

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Michelle Emerson in Austin, Texas with @google, and @googleedu. May be an image of laptop.

node.text:
Work smarter, not harder 💡🧠

One of the BEST decisions I made going into last school year was creating a grade level website (spoiler alert: I didn’t ACTUALLY teach at Fake Elementary School… this is just an example 😂)! 💻

This website acted as the one-stop-shop for EVERYTHING! We had teacher information, contact information, curriculum information, sign ups for instruments (how they did that virtually last year I STILL don’t understand), and more!

The best part?! YOU CAN REUSE IT YEAR AFTER YEAR! Once you create your website, you can hide elements so parents don’t see them and then you can make the elements visible at any time! It’s a total game changer! 😍

How did I create this?! I just used Google Sites (which is completely free). All I had to do was pop in my own images, text, and other fancy things like links and documents and it was done! 👌🏻

I promise… it really isn’t difficult! I even have a tutorial video to show you how to do it! 🎉 Check it out using the link below:
bit.ly/teachervlog252

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Michelle Emerson on July 26, 2021 tagging @youtube, and @pocketfulofprimary. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text:
5 years ago I took a chance and uploaded my first YouTube video for teachers 🎥

It was a huge step outside of my comfort zone as an introvert but I needed an outlet for my teaching passion because my family and friends could only tolerate so much 😂

I shared a pencil sharpener I loved (please don’t go and find it because it is just as embarrassing as it sounds 😂) and began uploading weekly videos to document the behind the scenes of teaching, share my ideas, and help make other teachers’ lives easier. I wanted to be for others what I so desperately needed my first year of teaching.

Fast forward to today… I now have over half a million subscribers 😳 I still can’t even wrap my head around that!

5 years of constant hard work, dedication, and sacrifice has completely transformed my life in ways I never even imagined. Grateful doesn’t even begin to cover it.

Thank you to everyone who has believed in me, encouraged me, and supported me because I am a better person and teacher today as a result 🖤

node.text:
HOW is it almost the end of July?!

The past few weeks have been a BLUR! We have officially been in our new house for a month which is insane because I accidentally walked into the guest bedroom earlier thinking it was the master bedroom so I obviously am still getting used to the change 😂

After the first two weeks of unpacking and getting settled, my parents came to stay with us (which they are going to make a little more permanent because they are now moving to Texas too 😂) and then we headed to Florida for a week.

We enjoyed a little bit of Disney (Hollywood Studios to be exact because that’s our FAVORITE park) and a day at Universal before and after #gytoxorlando before heading home.

But looking at the rest of the summer, I still have SO many things I want to accomplish! First, I am SO excited that Bridget will be coming to visit me in a little less than 2 weeks and I get to pay her pack for all the times she has hosted me at her house.

I also want to spend lots of time outside (including a picnic because @mrpocketfulofprimary and I realized that we have never actually done one) and reading for enjoyment (because I don’t remember the last time I did that).

What’s left on your summer bucket list? I’m always looking to expand my list and would love some ideas! 💡

node.text:
There’s something about getting home from a trip, unpacking, doing laundry, and cleaning the house that makes you feel BRAND NEW! ✨

Today has been a “get back to routine day”:
▪️Wake up at my usual time
▪️Drink lots of water
▪️Workout
▪️Conquer power list
▪️Tidy up
▪️Spend time refilling my cup

Our house is clean, organized, and ready for a productive week ahead! 😍

If you want a full tour of my house organization (you get to see inside all my cabinets and drawers), check out my YouTube video! 
🎥: bit.ly/teachervlog291

node.text:
I am a teacher. Always.

When I made the decision to not teach in the classroom this upcoming school year, I was terrified. There were a lot of reasons to be afraid, but what scared me the most was the thought of losing my identity as a teacher.

“Teacher” has always been one of the biggest defining aspects of who I am. Not just as my career, but who I am as a person. Stepping down from the traditional role of “teacher” in a classroom with students meant letting go of that piece of me.

At least, that’s what I mistakenly thought.

I’ve come to realize that being a teacher can take on so many different forms. My passion was initially ignited by teaching students (technically this started when I held school for the neighborhood children on my front porch as a kid, although that’s a story for a different day) but lately what lights my soul on fire is teaching teachers.

Being able to make another teacher’s job easier (after experiencing so many struggles of my own in the classroom) GIVES. ME. SO. MUCH. JOY.

I am no longer afraid because I’ve realized that I will always be a teacher in some capacity. Teaching teachers is still teaching.

More than ever, I’m motivated to make a difference. I am inspired to help. I am excited to improve my abilities. Why? Because I am a teacher. Always.

I’ve been lucky enough to spend the past 4 days presenting to over a thousand teachers from across the country at the @getyourteachon National Conference! 🍎🤯🎉

Professional development with teachers who are so passionate, engaged, and willing to try new things is the BEST! 🥰

I learned so many things from the other incredible presenters and amazing  attendees and I stepped out of my comfort zone in a BIG way. My heart is full and my drive to continue to improve is at an all time high 🖤

Thank you @heyhopeking and @heywadeking for allowing me to be a part of this incredible experience and thank you to all the Magic Squad members who made this conference possible! 🎉  Grateful doesn’t even begin to cover it.

📸: @cafeyestilo &
@david_erickson_photography
